This sub-routine is the heart of the brute force approach. The intuition is that anagrams have identical character multiset, which when sorted produces the same sequence. By sorting both strings and comparing the results, we can determine anagram status in O(k log k) time. The algorithm is straightforward: given two strings s1 and s2, we sort each string (typically using built-in sort like sorted() in Python), then compare the sorted results for equality. If equal, they are anagrams; otherwise, they are not. The time complexity is O(k log k) where k is the length of the strings (assuming comparison-based sort). Space complexity is O(k) for the sorted copies. This feeds into the full problem by being the core comparison operation used in the nested loops. Common mistakes include not handling empty strings properly (empty strings sort to empty strings), forgetting that sorting is case-sensitive (though the problem typically uses lowercase), and inefficiently re-sorting the same string multiple times in the full solution. The real code pattern is simple but crucial for correctness.

Pseudocode:
function are_anagrams(s1, s2):
   return sorted(s1) == sorted(s2)

This building block creates sorted versions of strings, which serve as canonical representations for anagram grouping. The intuition is that sorting a string rearranges its characters in a consistent order (typically alphabetical), so any anagrams will produce identical sorted strings. This transforms the anagram detection problem into a simple string equality check. The algorithm is simple: for each input string, create a new string that is the sorted version of its characters. In Python, this can be done with ''.join(sorted(s)). The time complexity is O(k log k) per string for sorting, and space complexity is O(k) for the sorted copy. This feeds into the core logic by providing the precomputed sorted strings that are compared in the nested loops. In the full brute force solution, we compute these sorted strings once at the beginning to avoid re-sorting multiple times. Common mistakes include not converting the sorted list back to a string (which may cause comparison issues), forgetting that sorting is case-sensitive, and not handling empty strings correctly (sorted('') returns an empty list). The real code pattern is straightforward but essential for efficiency in the full solution.

Pseudocode:
function sort_string(s):
   return ''.join(sorted(s))

